## [1] "Directory already exists."

Lets load in the data from Iris. In total, there are 13 possible driver mutations. However, some of these are fixed on the ancestor or reference. If we exclude these, there are only 9 drivers that arent fixed.

Non-ancestral Drivers
SNP AA_Change Gene Haplotype
T3586C Phe50Ser M genome-1-1
C6776A Ala440Glu F cluster 12
C7036T Gln527* F both
T7293C Ile8Thr H both
T7302C Phe11Ser H subclonal
G6775A Ala440Thr F subclonal
G7033T Glu526* F subclonal
T7304C Tyr12His H cluster 6
T7301C Phe11Leu H subclonal

Of these 9 drivers, were able to haplotype 3 of them, however, the remaining 6 lack phylogenetic context. Lets see what these are.

Weve already know about two of these SNPs - C7036T and T7293C - that we believe are on both genome-1 and genome-2. Of the remaining four new driver SNPs without phylogenetic context, only G6775A and G7033T are high-enough frequency to reasonable assign to on of the clusters weve already determined.

SNP: G7033T

This is an interesting SNP because, like C7036T (shown above), its a stop codon in the C-terminal domain of the Fusion protein.

Coding Effect of G7033T
SNP AA_Change Gene
G7033T Glu526* F

There are three tissues that have this mutation at an appreciable frequency (> 5% Allele Frequency).

Tissues with G7033T
SNP AA_Change Gene Tissue
G7033T Glu526* F Brain Stem
G7033T Glu526* F Upper Brain Stem
G7033T Glu526* F Internal Capsule

Overall, this SNP is at higher frequency in the lower regions of the brain.

Now, lets see if there any bridging reads in these tissues that allow us to assign this SNP to an existing cluster. Below, I filtered the bridging read counts for only reads that: 1. Overlap position 7033 (where the driver is) 2. Both SNPs are represented in more than 5% of bridging reads 3. Are only from the three tissues above

Then, I arranged them by the count of reads that contain both SNPs (11).

Whats really interesting here is that there is strong evidence that this stop codon mutation (F-526*) is not linked to reads with the other stop codon driver at position 7036 (F-527*). This makes sense biologically if these Fusion C-terminal mutants are positively selected.
